
__global__ functions are the interface.  They are called from the host and run on the device.
eg:

__global__ void foo(int x) { ... }

__host__ void
bar(int x)
{
	foo<<<gridDim, blockDim, sharedMem, stream>>>(x);

	/*
	1. gridDim — number of blocks (required)
	2. blockDim — threads per block (required)
	3. sharedMem — bytes of dynamically allocated shared memory per block (default 0)
	4. stream — CUDA stream for asynchronous execution (default 0, the default stream)
	*/
}

The triple cheveron specifies the "execution configuration".

Error checking:
CUDA does not maintain a stack of errors, just the most recent.
cudaPeekAtLastError() returns the last CUDA runtime error without clearing it. Contrast
with cudaGetLastError(), which returns the error and resets it to cudaSuccess.  If
there have been no errors, each return cudaSuccess, which is an enum.  Eg:

cudaError_t err = cudaPeekAtLastError();
if (err != cudaSuccess) {
	const char *s = cudaGetErrorString(err);
}
